the thigh. It serves as a passageway for the femoral artery, femoral vein, and the saphenous nerve, among other structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evastus medialis\u003C/strong\u003E forms the anterior and lateral boundaries of the adductor canal. This canal is a narrow passageway in the middle third of the thigh, through which important neurovascular structures pass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdductor longus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle forms part of the medial boundary of the canal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdductor magnus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle forms the posterior boundary of the canal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESartorius\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle forms the roof of the canal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGracilis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is not directly involved in forming the boundaries of the adductor canal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The adductor canal is a passageway in the thigh that allows for the passage of major blood vessels and nerves.","The anterior and lateral boundaries of the adductor canal are formed by the vastus medialis muscle.","The adductor canal is also known as the subsartorial canal or Hunter\u0027s canal."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/